<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-01-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-01-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="485" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d485">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 855.51/5</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-01-17">17 January,
                                1919</date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I would be obliged if you
                        would, as you suggest, reply to this<note n="34" xml:id="d485fn34">See
                            Secretary Lansing’s letter of Jan. 14, regarding proposed loans to
                            Belgium, <ref target="#pg_567">p. 567</ref>.</note> in the sense
                        suggested by General Bliss.</p>
                    <p>Cordially and sincerely yours,</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Woodrow Wilson</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>